<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910507-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>910507-0030.</DOCID><HL>   Technology Brief -- Microsoft Corp.:   Raid at Westinghouse Unit   Yields Unauthorized Copies</HL><DATE>05/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   ACAD MSFT WX</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><RE>BRAZIL (BR)CALIFORNIA (CA)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   Microsoft Corp. said Brazilian authorities discoveredunauthorized copies of Microsoft computer programs in a raidon the offices of a unit of Westinghouse Electric Corp.   The Redmond, Wash.-based software maker said theWestinghouse unit could face civil fines of as much as $2million for copyright infringement if it doesn't settle thematter. It said Westinghouse has until May 27 to settle orface the filing of civil charges in the Brazilian courts.</LP><TEXT>   Westinghouse couldn't be reached to comment.   Microsoft is known in the software business for waging anaggressive campaign against computer users who make copies ofsoftware on the sly. It said the raid took place April 23 atthe offices of Westinghouse Brazil in Sao Paulo, in responseto a complaint filed in Brazil by Microsoft and AutodeskInc., Sausalito, Calif., another software concern.   Microsoft said Brazilian officers seized &quot;numerousunauthorized copies&quot; of Microsoft's MS-DOS operating softwareand an Autodesk program used in computer-aided design.</TEXT></DOC>